{{Infobox song | Name = Around the World | written = 1956 | Published = 1956 | Writer = [[Harold Adamson]], [[Victor Young]] }} "'''Around the World'''" was the [[theme tune]] from the [[1956 in film|1956]] [[Film|movie]] ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' <ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0048960/soundtrack Around the World in 80 Days (1956) - Soundtracks] from [[Internet Movie Database]]</ref> In the film, only an instrumental version of the song appeared, although the vocal version has become by far the better known one. The song was [[songwriter|written]] by [[Harold Adamson]] and [[Victor Young]]; Young died in 1956, several weeks after the film's release and he received the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Academy Award for Best Music, Scoring of a Dramatic or Comedy Picture]] posthumously. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0048960/awards]</ref> Young's orchestral version was a #13 hit on the Billboard charts in 1957.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits|date=2004|publisher=Billboard Books|location=New York|isbn=0-8230-7499-4|page=694|edition=8th}}</ref> The recording by Bing Crosby was the B-side of the Victor Young version in 1957, on Festival SP45-1274 in Australia, and was a joint charting success.
==Recorded versions== The song has been [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]], among others, by: {{div col|colwidth=22em}} *[[Karen Akers]] *[[John Arpin]] *[[Nora Aunor]] *[[Brook Benton]] (on the album "Endlessly" - 1959)<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Brook-Benton-Endlessly/master/424098|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> *[[Stanley Black]] *[[Liam Burrows]] *[[The Chordettes]] - for their album ''Never on Sunday'' (1962).<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Chordettes-Never-On-Sunday/master/907664|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Nat King Cole]] - recorded August 8, 1957.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nat King Cole Discography|url=https://www.jazzdisco.org/nat-king-cole/discography/|website=jazzdisco.org|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *The Columbia Ballroom Orchestra *[[Ray Conniff]] - included in the EP ''Ray Conniff Around the World'' (1963).<ref>{{cite web|title=45cat.com|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/agg20043|website=45cat.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Sam Cooke]] - included in his album ''[[Songs by Sam Cooke]]'' (1958) *[[Bing Crosby]] ([[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] top hit (#25) in [[1957 in music|1957]], No. 5 hit in UK <ref name="auto">{{cite book|title=British Hit Singles & Albums|date=2004|publisher=Guinness World Records Ltd|isbn=1-904994-00-8|edition=18th}}</ref>) *[[Gracie Fields]] (No. 8 hit in UK<ref name="auto"/>) *[[Eddie Fisher (singer)|Eddie Fisher]] - a 1956 single release.<ref>{{cite web|title=45cat.com|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/476677us|website=45cat.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Connie Francis]] - included in her album ''[[Connie Francis Sings "Never on Sunday"]]'' (1961). *[[Buddy Greco]] - a single release in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|title=45cat.com|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/52204|website=45cat.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Ronnie Hilton]] (No. 4 hit in UK<ref name="auto"/>) *[[Harry James]] *[[Joni James]] - included in the album ''100 Strings & Joni in Hollywood'' (1961).<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Joni-James-100-Strings-Joni-In-Hollywood/master/695560|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Jonah Jones]] *[[James Last]] *[[Steve Lawrence]] - for his album ''Winners!'' (1963)<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Steve-Lawrence-Winners/master/342873|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> *[[Brenda Lee]] - for her album ''[[Emotions (Brenda Lee album)|Emotions]]'' (1961) *The [[Mantovani]] Orchestra ([[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] top hit (#12) in [[1957 in music|1957]], No. 20 hit in UK<ref name="auto"/>) *[[The McGuire Sisters]] *[[Bette Midler]] for the live album "[[Live at Last (Bette Midler album)|Live At Last]]" (1977). *[[Matt Monro]] - included in his album ''From Hollywood with Love'' (1964).<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Matt-Monro-From-Hollywood-With-Love/master/952182|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Jane Morgan]] and The Troubadours - included in her album ''Fascination'' (1957).<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Jane-Morgan-With-Troubadors-Fascination/master/402656|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[Emile Pandolfi]] *[[André Prévin]] *[[Louis Prima]] *[[George Sanders]] *[[The Shirelles]] *[[Frank Sinatra]], in [[Come Fly with Me (Frank Sinatra album)|Come Fly with Me]] 1958 Capitol LP, arr & cond Billy May *[[Kay Starr]] - in her album ''Movin'!'' (1959).<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs.com|url=https://www.discogs.com/Kay-Starr-Movin/master/328755|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> *[[The Supremes]] - a 1965 recording included in the expanded CD version of ''[[There's a Place for Us]]'' (2004) *[[Paul Sullivan (composer)|Paul Sullivan]] *[[The Sundowners (band)|The Sundowners]] *[[Billy Vaughn]] *[[Bobby Vinton]] - 