'''Carola Hansson-Boëthius''' (born 7 September 1942) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] novelist, dramatist and translator.<ref name=ll>{{cite web|url=http://nordicwomensliterature.net/writer/hansson-carola-0|title=Hansson, Carola|author=Lisbeth Larsson|work=The History of Nordic Women's Literature|accessdate=24 January 2015|language=}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==Biography== Born in [[Stockholm]], Carola Hansson studied Russian and history of art and literature at [[Uppsala University]]. Together with [[Karin Lindén]], she authored her first work in 1980, ''Samtal med kvinnor i Moskva'', translated into English as ''Moscow Women: Thirteen Interviews'', published in 1983.<ref name="HanssonLidén1983">{{cite book|last1=Hansson|first1=Carola|last2=Lidén|first2=Karin |author3=George Blecher |author4=Lone Thygesen-Blecher|title=Moscow Women: Thirteen Interviews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EWeM_GBfM4sC|year=1983|publisher=[[Allison & Busby]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-85031-565-3}}</ref>
Hansson's first novel, ''Det drömda barnet'' (The Dream Child) was published in 1983, presenting the feelings of fear and longing she experienced in childhood and which typify her later works, especially ''Pojken från Jerusalem'' (1986), ''De två trädgårdarna'' (1989) and ''Resan till det blå huset'' (1991). She became widely recognized in 1994 with ''Andrej'', a novel about the [[Leo Tolstoy|Tolstoy]] family, which was well received by the critics.<ref name=ll/><ref name=norstets/> Her most recent work, ''Med ett namn som mitt'' (With a Name like Mine, 2009), follows on from ''Andrej'' in an episode based on a meeting between the author and someone who claims to have known Tolstoy's son, [[Ilya Tolstoy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/litteratur/tillbaka-hos-tolstoj_3432801.svd|title=Tillbaka hos Tolstoj |publisher=SvD Kultur|accessdate=24 January 2015 |language=Swedish}}</ref>
==Bibliography== * ''Samtal med kvinnor i Moskva'' 1980 (non-fiction, authored together with Karin Lidén) * ''Kvinnan och Ryssland'' 1981 (non-fiction with Karin Lidén) * ''Det drömda barnet'', novel, 1983 * ''Stilleben i vitt'', novel, 1985 * ''Pojken från Jerusalem'', novel, 1987 * ''De två trädgårdarna'', novel, 1989 * ''Resan till det blå huset'', novel, 1991 * ''Steinhof'', novel, 1997, * ''Den älskvärde'', novel. 2000 * ''Mästarens dröm'', novel, 2005 * [[Leo_Tolstoy | Leo Tolstoy's]] family [[trilogy]]: ** ''Andrej'', novel, 1994 ** ''Med ett namn som mitt'', 2009 ** ''Masja'', 2015
==Awards== Hansson has received several awards including the Swedish Radio Novel Prize in 1995 and the [[Dobloug Prize]] in 2006.<ref name=norstets>{{cite web|url=http://www.norstedts.se/forfattare/Alfabetiskt/H/Carola-Hansson/|title=Carola Hansson|publisher=Norstets|accessdate=24 January 2015 |language=}}</ref>
