{{for|the Elizabethan farm house in Wigan, England|Worthington Hall, Wigan}} {{Infobox NRHP | name = Worthington Hall | nrhp_type = | image = WORTHINGTON HALL, MONROE COUNTY, PA.jpg | caption = The rebuilt hall is a copy of the original. | location= Worthington Ave. at Shawnee-on-the-Delaware, [[Smithfield Township, Monroe County, Pennsylvania|Smithfield Township, Pennsylvania]] | coordinates = {{coord|41|00|45.6|N|75|06|31.7|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Pennsylvania#USA | built = 1904 | added = April 14, 1978 | delisted = December 18, 1986 | area = {{convert|0.8|acre}} | governing_body = Local | refnum = 78002433<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }}
'''Worthington Hall''', now known as the '''Shawnee Playhouse''', was a historic [[theatre]] located in [[Smithfield Township, Monroe County, Pennsylvania|Smithfield Township]], [[Monroe County, Pennsylvania]]. It was built in 1904.<ref name="shawnee">[http://www.theshawneeplayhouse.com/history.htm Shawnee Playhouse History & Mission]</ref>
It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1978.<ref name="nris"/> It was delisted in 1986 after being demolished following a fire—caused by arson—on June 24, 1985.<ref name="shawnee"/> With help from the people of [[Shawnee on Delaware]], the Seabees, the Hughes Foundation, the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], [[The National Trust]], a [[Community Development Block Grant]], and generous donations from many individuals and friends, the playhouse was rebuilt.
